5 PART I. REVISIONS TO BALLOT COUNTING PROCEDURE
6 SECTION 1.1.(a) G.S. 163-182.2(a)(4) is recodified as G.S. 163-182.2(a2).
7 SECTION 1.1.(b) G.S. 163-182.2(a)(6) is recodified as G.S. 163-182.2(a3).
8 SECTION 1.1.(c) G.S. 163-182.2, as amended by S.L. 2024-57 and this section,
9 reads as rewritten:
10 "§ 163-182.2. Initial counting of official ballots.
11 (a) The initial counting of official ballots cast at the precinct on election day and under
12 Part 5 of Article 14A of this Chapter shall be conducted according to the following principles:
13 (1) Vote counting of ballots cast at the precinct on election day shall occur
14 immediately after the polls close and shall be continuous until completed. If
15 ballots cast under Part 5 of Article 14A of this Chapter are counted
16 electronically, that count shall commence at the time the polls close. If ballots
17 cast under Part 5 of Article 14A of this Chapter are paper ballots counted
18 manually, that count shall commence at the same time as mail-in absentee
19 ballots cast under Article 20 or Article 21A of this Chapter are counted.
20 (2) Vote counting at the precinct shall be conducted with the participation of
21 precinct officials of all political parties then present. Vote counting at the
22 county board of elections shall be conducted in the presence or under the
23 supervision of board members of all political parties then present.
24 (3) Any member of the public wishing to witness the vote count at any level shall
25 be allowed to do so. No witness shall interfere with the orderly counting of
26 the official ballots. Witnesses shall not participate in the official counting of
27 official ballots.
28 (4) Recodified.
29 (5) Precinct officials shall provide a preliminary report of the vote counting on
30 election day to the county board of elections as quickly as possible. The
31 preliminary report shall be unofficial, has no binding effect upon the official
32 county canvass to follow, and shall include the number of provisional ballots
33 cast in that precinct.
34 (6) Recodified.
35 (a1) The initial counting of official ballots cast under Part 5 of Article 14A of this Chapter
36 shall be conducted according to the following principles:
*H958-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) Vote counting shall occur between the hours of 9:00 A.M. and 5:00 P.M. on
2 election day at the hour and place stated in a resolution adopted by the county
3 board at least two weeks prior to the time the voting place opens in accordance
4 with G.S. 163-166.25. The county board shall not reveal the result of the count
5 prior to the close of polls on election day.
6 (2) Vote counting shall be conducted in the presence or under the supervision of
7 county board members of all political parties then present.
8 (3) Any member of the public wishing to witness the vote count shall be allowed
9 to do so. No witness shall interfere with the orderly counting of the official
10 ballots. Witnesses shall not participate in the official counting of official
11 ballots.
12 (a2) If the county board finds that an individual voting a provisional official ballot (i) was
13 registered in the county as provided in 163-82.1, (ii) voted in the proper precinct under
14 G.S. 163-55 and G.S. 163-57, and (iii) was otherwise eligible to vote, the provisional official
15 ballots shall be counted by the county board no later than 5:00 P.M. on the third fifth business
16 day after the election. County boards may review for approval any provisional official ballots
17 cast under Part 5 of Article 14A of this Chapter and take preparatory steps for the count prior to
18 election day, using the same procedures used for counting absentee ballots under G.S. 163-234(3)
19 as long as the preparatory steps do not reveal the result of the count prior to the close of polls on
20 election day. Except as provided in G.S. 163-82.15(e), if the county board finds that an individual
21 voting a provisional official ballot (i) did not vote in the proper precinct under G.S. 163-55 and
22 G.S. 163-57, (ii) is not registered in the county as provided in G.S. 163-82.1, or (iii) is otherwise
23 not eligible to vote, the ballot shall not be counted. If a voter was properly registered to vote in
24 the election by the county board, no mistake of an election official in giving the voter a ballot or
25 in failing to comply with G.S. 163-82.15 or G.S. 163-166.11 shall serve to prevent the counting
26 of the vote on any ballot item the voter was eligible by registration and qualified by residency to
27 vote. When an individual has voted a provisional official ballot after completing an affidavit
28 under G.S. 163-166.16(d), and the county board has not found the affidavit to be valid within
29 five business days after the election because the county board has grounds to believe the affidavit
30 is false, the county board shall determine whether to count the provisional official ballot by the
31 date of the county canvass.
32 (a3) In counties that use any certified mechanical or electronic voting system, subject to
33 the sample counts under G.S. 163-182.1 and subdivision (2) of subsection (b) of this section, and
34 of a hand-to-eye recount under G.S. 163-182.7 and G.S. 163-182.7A, a county board of elections
35 shall rely in its canvass on the mechanical or electronic count of the vote rather than the full
36 hand-to-eye count of the paper ballots or records. In the event of a material discrepancy between
37 the electronic or mechanical count and a hand-to-eye count or recount, the hand-to-eye count or
38 recount shall control, except where paper ballots or records have been lost or destroyed or where
39 there is another reasonable basis to conclude that the hand-to-eye count is not the true count.
40 (a4) Any resolution required by this section shall be published once a week for two weeks
41 prior to the election, in a newspaper having general circulation in the county. Notice may
42 additionally be made on a radio or television station or both, but the notice shall be in addition to
43 the newspaper and other required notice.
44 (b) The State Board shall promulgate rules for the initial counting of all official ballots.
45 All election officials shall be governed by those rules. In promulgating those rules, the State
46 Board shall adhere to the following guidelines:
47 (1) For each voting system used, the rules shall specify the role of precinct
48 officials and of the county board of elections in the initial counting of official
49 ballots.
50 (2) For optical scan and direct record electronic voting systems, and for any other
51 voting systems in which ballots are counted other than on paper by hand and
