30 "(e1) Curable Deficiencies. – If a container-return envelope contains a curable deficiency,
31 the county board shall promptly notify the voter of the deficiency and the manner in which the
32 voter may cure the deficiency. Curable deficiencies are deficiencies that can be cured with
33 supplemental documentation or attestation provided by the voter, including when any of the
34 following occurs:
35 (1) The voter did not sign the voter certification as required by
36 G.S. 163-231(a)(4).
37 (2) The voter signed the application in the wrong place on the application.
38 (3) The voter failed to include with the container-return envelope a photocopy of
39 identification described in G.S. 163-166.16(a) or an affidavit as described in
40 G.S. 163-166.16(d)(1), (d)(2), or (d)(3), as required by subsection (f1) of this
41 section.
42 The identification of the two persons witnessing the casting of the absentee ballot in
43 accordance with G.S. 163-231(a) is not a curable deficiency. Any container-return envelope with
44 a curable deficiency that is transmitted to the county board shall be considered timely if cure
45 documentation is received no later than 12:00 P.M. on the third fifth business day after the
46 election. Cure documentation may be transmitted via email to the county board if the deficiency
47 is one described in subdivision (3) of this subsection. The notification of voters regarding curable
48 deficiencies is an administrative task that may be performed by county board staff and is not
49 required to be performed at an absentee meeting as provided for in subsection (f) of this section.
50 The voter shall be notified of curable deficiencies by mail, and by telephone or email if the
