21 PART VI. SIGNATURE VERIFICATION PILOT PROGRAM
22 SECTION 6.(a) The State Board of Elections shall select 10 counties in the State in
23 which to conduct a pilot program during the primary held in 2026 for signature verification on
24 executed absentee ballots. In selecting the 10 counties for the pilot, the State Board of Elections
25 shall seek diversity of population size, regional location, and demographic composition, and may
26 use the same 10 counties that were selected for the pilot program in accordance with S.L.
27 2023-140. The pilot program shall consist of county boards of elections using signature
28 verification software to check the signatures of voters noted on all executed absentee ballots
29 received by the county boards of elections in the 2026 primary. The State Board of Elections
30 shall select the signature verification software and ensure that the software is available for all 10
31 counties to use in the 2026 primary. The State Board of Elections shall assist the selected county
32 boards of elections in implementing the signature verification software, including assisting the
33 selected county boards of elections in any training needed on how the software is to be used for
34 signature matching on executed absentee ballots.
35 SECTION 6.(b) The State Board of Elections shall closely monitor the pilot program
36 established in this section. The selected county boards of elections shall report to the State Board
37 of Elections its findings on the use of the signature verification software during the 2026 primary,
38 including all of the following:
39 (1) Whether the signature verification software was used for all executed absentee
40 ballots, and what the voter signature on the executed absentee ballot was
41 matched against.
42 (2) How many executed absentee ballots were counted by the county board of
43 elections in the 2026 primary.
44 (3) How many executed absentee ballots were flagged by the signature
45 verification software, and any information known on how close of a match the
46 signatures must be for the signature match software to not flag the voter's
47 signature.
48 (4) Information on how the signature matching software flagged an executed
49 absentee ballot with a signature that did not match the signature on file for the
50 voter, including any known information on the rate of error in the software.
House Bill 958-Second Edition Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 6.(c) In implementing the pilot program established in this section, no
2 executed absentee ballot shall be rejected by the county board of elections for failing any
3 signature verification. All executed absentee ballots that are otherwise eligible to be counted in
4 accordance with Chapter 163 of the General Statutes shall be counted.
5 SECTION 6.(d) The State Board of Elections shall report its findings, along with
6 any recommendations, to the General Assembly on or before May 1, 2026. The report shall be
7 delivered to the Joint Legislative Elections Oversight Committee and shall also include the
8 following:
9 (1) A compilation of the information reported from the selected county boards of
10 elections as required by subsection (b) of this section.
11 (2) The estimated cost to implement signature verification for absentee ballots
12 statewide.
13 (3) Any suggested law changes to fully implement signature verification
14 statewide for absentee ballots, including suggestions on a process for how a
15 voter can cure a deficiency related to signature verification of absentee ballots.
16 (4) Any other information relevant to signature verification of absentee ballots.
17
18 PART VII. TRAINING FOR COUNTY BOARDS OF ELECTIONS
19 SECTION 7.1. The School of Government at the University of North Carolina at
20 Chapel Hill shall work jointly with the State Board of Elections to develop a uniform curriculum
21 to provide trainings for county directors of elections and employees of county boards of elections
22 on the election laws and procedures as provided for in Chapter 163 of the General Statutes.
23 SECTION 7.2. The State Board of Elections shall partner with local community
24 colleges to provide a location in which any training conducted by the State Board of Elections or
25 a county board of elections may be held.
26
27 PART VIII. EFFECTIVE DATE
28 SECTION 8. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
29 law.
